  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="pr_counterexample"></xref></title>
    <p>
      A counterexample for this statement will be values of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> for which 5 divides <m>a</m> or 5 divides <m>b</m>,
      and 5 does not divide <m>5a + b</m>.
      One counterexample for the statement is <m>a = 5</m> and <m>b = 1</m>.
      For these values,
      the hyothesis is true since 5 divides <m>a</m> and the conclusion is false since
      <m>5a + b = 26</m> and 5 does not divide 26.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="pr_congruence"></xref></title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Some integers that are congruent to 5 modulo 8 are <m>-11, -3, 5, 13</m>, and 21.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\left\{ \left. x \in \Z \right| x \equiv 5 \pmod 8 \right\} = \left\{ \ldots, -19, -11, -3, 5, 13, 21, 29, \ldots \right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="pr_congans3">
        <p>
          For example, <m>-3 + 5 = 2</m>,
          <m>-11 + 29 = 18</m>, <m>13 + 21 = 34</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If we subtract 2 from any of the sums obtained in Part<nbsp/><xref ref="pr_congans3"/>, the result will be a multiple of 8.
          This means that the sum is congruent to 2 modulo 8.
          For example, <m>2 - 2 = 0</m>,
          <m>18 - 2 = 16</m>, <m>34 - 2 = 32</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="pr_congruence2"></xref></title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          To prove that 8 divides <m>(a + b - 2)</m>,
          we can prove that there exists an integer <m>q</m> such that <m>(a + b - 2) = 8q</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Since 8 divides <m>(a - 5)</m> and <m>(b - 5)</m>,
          there exist integers <m>k</m> and <m>m</m> such that
          <m>a - 5 = 8k</m> and <m>b - 5 = 8m</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>a = 5 + 8k</m> and <m>b = 5 + 8m</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>a + b - 2 = (5 + 8k) + (5 + 8m) - 2 = 8 + 8k + 8m = 8(1 + k + m)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <proof>
            <p>
              Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers and assume that
              <m>\mod{a}{5}{8}</m> and <m>\mod{b}{5}{8}</m>.
              We will prove that <m>\mod{(a + b)}{2}{8}</m>.
              Since 8 divides <m>(a - 5)</m> and <m>(b - 5)</m>,
              there exist integers <m>k</m> and <m>m</m> such that
              <m>a - 5 = 8k</m> and <m>b - 5 = 8m</m>.
              We then see that
              <md>
                <mrow>a + b - 2 \amp = (5 + 8k) + (5 + 8m) - 2</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = 8 + 8k + 8m</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = 8(1 + k + m)</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              By the closure properties of the integers,
              <m>(1 + k + m)</m> is an integer and so the last equation proves that 8 divides <m>(a + b - 2)</m> and hence,
              <m>\mod{(a + b)}{2}{8}</m>.
              This proves that if <m>\mod{a}{5}{8}</m> and <m>\mod{b}{5}{8}</m>,
              then <m>\mod{(a + b)}{2}{8}</m>.
            </p>
          </proof>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
